Reading Stacktraces

This page is your friend. All the info is there.

The ADIS 16470 is a 3-Axis gyroscope. When you call “getRate()”, you need to pass in which axis you want to read. See:

github.wpilib.org

ADIS16470_IMU (WPILib API 2024.1.1)

declaration: package: edu.wpi.first.wpilibj, class: ADIS16470_IMU

If you are not familiar with those terms, see: Yaw (rotation) - Wikipedia

It looks like previous versions of this library did not require this parameter, and it always returned the value for Yaw. See this for 2023’s version of the library:

https://first.wpi.edu/wpilib/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/ADIS16470_IMU.html#getRate()

You will see this change described partway down this page:

FIRST Robotics Competition Documentation

New for 2024

A number of improvements have been made to FRC ® Control System software for 2024. This article will describe and provide a brief overview of the new changes and features as well as a more complete...

Regarding the above comment about interpreting stack traces: What you are encountering is not a stack trace. A stack trace occurs when an uncaught exception happens at runtime. It shows you the “stack” of methods being called at the time of the exception. For example, if A() calls B() which callls C() and C() fails, it will show you A—> B—> C. What you are actually seeing is an exception that occurs at build time. These happens which the compiler sees that you are doing something structurally incorrect; in this case, you are missing a required input parameter into that function call.
